body.value:
National Housing and Construction Company Ltd (NHCC) is a venerable institution with a 50-year history, originally founded as the National Housing Corporation under Ugandan government ownership. Established by an Act of Parliament (Cap 321) in 1964, NHCC has evolved into Uganda's foremost housing developer.

The company's primary mandate is to augment the country's housing stock, revitalize the housing industry, and promote home ownership among Ugandans within a structured framework. NHCC plays a pivotal role in fostering organized housing environments and is instrumental in advancing Uganda's housing sector.

body.value:
The Ministry of Finance (MOF) is one of Ethiopia's key macroeconomic institutions with a mandate that focuses on fiscal policy, public finance, and external economic relations. The ministry's mandate was further extended following recent reform efforts. Its responsibilities include:

  1. Economic Cooperation:

    • Lead and coordinate economic cooperation with bilateral, multilateral, and regional organizations.
    • Monitor the impact of such links on the country's economic performance.

  2. Financial Asset Management:

    • Act as the depository and safeguard the Federal Government's shares, negotiable and non-negotiable instruments, and other similar financial assets.

  3. Procurement and Property Management:

    • Establish and supervise the procurement and property management system of the Federal Government.

  4. Budgeting and Accounting:

    • Establish budgeting, accounting, disbursement, and internal audit systems for the Federal Government.
    • Ensure these systems are harmonized and aligned with international standards at both federal and regional government levels.

  5. Privatization:

    • Prepare necessary documents for the privatization of public enterprises.
    • Facilitate the privatization process in collaboration with relevant government bodies.

These functions are crucial for maintaining fiscal discipline, ensuring efficient public financial management, and fostering economic growth through effective cooperation and resource management.

attributes.content: The Rwanda Development Board (RDB) is a government institution tasked with accelerating Rwanda's economic development by fostering private sector growth. Operating under the supervision of the Office of the President, RDB is governed by a Board of Directors comprising global entrepreneurs and experts.Established in 2008 from the merger of eight government institutions, RDB's primary aim was to create a One Stop Shop for business and investment. The institution has since been built on global expertise and modeled on international best practices.

body.value:
The Rwanda Development Board (RDB) is a government institution tasked with accelerating Rwanda's economic development by fostering private sector growth. Operating under the supervision of the Office of the President, RDB is governed by a Board of Directors comprising global entrepreneurs and experts.

Established in 2008 from the merger of eight government institutions, RDB's primary aim was to create a One Stop Shop for business and investment. The institution has since been built on global expertise and modeled on international best practices.

RDB offers several key services, including One Stop Center services (such as business and investment registration, visa facilitation, Environmental Impact Assessments, and tax incentives management), Investment Promotion, Investment Deals Negotiation, Export and Special Economic Zone (SEZ) Development, Tourism and Conservation, and Private Sector Skills Development.

RDB is dedicated to supporting investors throughout their entire investment journey, ensuring that Rwanda remains one of the most competitive places to do business in Africa and around the world.
